The orator, more or less consciously, in the composition of his phrases and sentences hits upon words which not only convey his meaning, but also are most pleasing in sound. But the effect, in respect to sound, depende partly on the shape of the word, that is, on the elemental sounds (rep- resented by letters) of which it is formed (see viii, 3, 16), and partly on the feet and measures which words make in the com- position.
